Basic information

  • Module name: Statistics for Environmental Scientists

  • Module code: ENV203

  • Credit value: 5

  • Learning outcomes

    This module provides training in statistics for environmental scientists. We emphasize the use of software to analyze real environmental data. We do not assume extensive prior knowledge. We will teach the essential theory alongside the practical components.

    1. Make sense of the statistical terms that appear in scientific papers and the media
    2. Summarize data using graphs, tables, and numerical summaries
    3. Choose appropriate statistical methods to answer research questions
    4. Use statistical software to apply these methods, and interpret the output

Save your script

Two recommended ways to save your script:

  1. In a .R file
  • File - New File - R Script. Hotkey ctrl+shift+N
  1. In a .Rmd file
  • File - New File - R Markdown
  • Click the knit button, which knits it into a .html file.
  • Now you can remove the lines from {r setup, include=FALSE} to the end and put your R script in chunks.

Demonstration: The New York Air Quality dataset shows daily air quality measurements in New York, May to September 1973. The measurements include mean ozone in parts per billion from 1300 to 1500 hours at Roosevelt Island, solar radiation in Langleys in the frequency band 4000â7700 Angstroms from 0800 to 1200 hours at Central Park, average wind speed in miles per hour at 0700 and 1000 hours at LaGuardia Airport, maximum daily temperature in degrees Fahrenheit at La Guardia Airport.

We plot some ugly graphs, including three scatter plots, a histogram, a box plot, a pair plot:

Some fancy graphs:

install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(df_aq) + geom_point(aes(x = Solar.R, y = Temp))

ggplot(df_aq) + geom_histogram(aes(Temp))

ggplot(df_aq) + geom_boxplot(aes(Temp))

df_aq$Month <- as.character(df_aq$Month)
ggplot(df_aq) + geom_boxplot(aes(y = Temp, fill = Month))

install.packages("GGally")
library(GGally)
library(GGally)
ggpairs(df_aq[, 1:5], aes(colour=Month, alpha=0.5))

New York air quality

The New York Air Quality dataset shows daily air quality measurements in New York, May to September 1973. The measurements include mean ozone in parts per billion from 1300 to 1500 hours at Roosevelt Island, solar radiation in Langleys in the frequency band 4000â7700 Angstroms from 0800 to 1200 hours at Central Park, average wind speed in miles per hour at 0700 and 1000 hours at LaGuardia Airport, maximum daily temperature in degrees Fahrenheit at La Guardia Airport.

Download the airquality.csv file from the Learning Mall and import it into R or other software.

  1. How many rows and columns does this data frame have?
  2. What was the temperature on June 22?
  3. What was the mean early afternoon ozone concentration (ppb) in June?
  4. What was the mean, maximum, minimum, median of the morning wind speed in the whole dataset?
  5. The temperature in the dataset was given in \(^\circ\)F. Add a new column for the temperature in \(^\circ\)C.
  6. Make a boxplot of the early afternoon ozone concentration in June.
  7. Make a histogram of the early afternoon ozone concentration in June.
  8. Save the data frame as a .csv file
  9. Save the boxplot and histogram as .pdf files.
  10. Report all the results above in a .pdf file or .html file.

ENV203 students

61 students participated the module ENV203 in the academic year 2020/2021. The ENV203 Students dateset shows the survey data about these students.

Download the students203.csv file from the Learning Mall and import it into R or other software.

  1. How many rows and columns does this data frame have?
  2. What is the star sign of the student No.Â 16?
  3. What is the mean height of all the students?
  4. What is the mean, maximum, minimum, median of the shoe size in the whole dataset?
  5. How many students like the life in Suzhou very much?
  6. Body mass index (BMI) is a measure of body fat based on height and weight that applies to adult men and women. Add a new column as the BMI.
  7. Make a scatter plot for the weight agains the height.
  8. Make a histogram of the BMI for the male students. Hint: use which(df203$Gender == "male") to choose the indice of male students.
  9. Make a pair plot of all the numeric variables in the dataset. Using different colors for each gender.
  10. Save the data frame as a .csv file
  11. Save the boxplot and histogram as .pdf files.
  12. Report all the results above in a .pdf file or .html file.

Groundwater TCE

Trichloroethylene (TCE) is reported by the EPA to be the most prevalent solvent contaminating groundwater at superfund sites in the United States. Exposure can result in effects to the immune and reproductive systems, liver, kidneys, central nervous system, and may affect fetal development during pregnancy. Long term exposures to TCE can increase the risk of kidney cancer. There is also evidence that TCE exposure can increase the risk for non-Hodgkinâs lymphoma and liver cancer.

The âtceâ dataset shows the TCE concentrations (mg/L) at 10 randomly selected groundwater monitoring wells before remediation and the same wells after remediation. Download the tce.csv file from the Learning Mall and import it into R or other software.

  1. How many rows and columns does this data frame have?
  2. What were the TCE concentrations of the well No.Â 5 before and after remediation?
  3. What were the mean, maximum, minimum, median of the TCE concentrations of all the wells before and after remediation, respectively?
  4. Make a boxplot for the TCE concentrations before and after remediation, respectively.
  5. Save the boxplot and histogram as pdf files.
  6. Report all the results above in a .pdf file or .html file.
